How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high in comparison with Europe?
The answer is simple, lacking competence that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical, because we have three mobile networks and its high coverage is over 100%.
In contrast, mobile operators like to complain that there is an extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÜ), Pavel Dvorák, also said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It may be true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Exactly the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market led to a high price decline, which also required classical operators to react.
At the same time, even before the entrance of piburons such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the market in Great Britain, similar voices were heard there as well as here.
There has been evidence that there is room for this type of operator and that they can be successful.
On the other hand, there is no need to look for examples too far.
In February of this year, we inform you about the star of the virtual Mobilking operator in Poland.
Only after a year or so, this operator was able to obtain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking there is the Penta group that, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is to concentrate on many more specific target groups.
In addition, to enable them to function effectively, they are enough with many less customers than a classic operator.
They do not bear relatively high costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, this type of virtual operators are usually profiled with low cost - they offer cheap calls and messages that, however, are often contrary to the most adjusted service offer.
Thus, for example, mobile Tesco in Great Britain offers SMS at least half the price for competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good hit for a trivial group target.
